Why is this useful?

Imagine transferring money between two bank accounts.
You must lock:
Account A
Account B

If you lock only Account A and fail to lock Account B:
You should not continue.
You also should not keep Account A locked.

std::try_lock() solves this automatically.

std::try_lock() is used when we need to lock multiple mutexes. If it cannot lock all of them, it automatically ***
releases any mutexes it has already locked, so we don't end up holding only a subset of the required locks.

=========================================================
std::try_lock() (C++11) - Interview Notes
=========================================================

What is std::try_lock()?
---------------------------------------------------------

std::try_lock() is a C++11 free function that attempts to
lock multiple mutexes without blocking.

It tries to lock each mutex one by one in the order provided.

=========================================================
Syntax
=========================================================

int result = std::try_lock(m1, m2, m3);

=========================================================
Return Value
=========================================================

Returns -1
    -> All mutexes were successfully locked.

Returns 0, 1, 2, ...
    -> Zero-based index of the mutex that could not be locked.

=========================================================
How it Works
=========================================================

1. Attempts to lock each mutex in the given order.

2. If all mutexes are locked successfully,
   it returns -1.

3. If locking any mutex fails,
   it immediately unlocks all previously locked mutexes.

4. If an exception occurs while locking,
   all previously locked mutexes are unlocked before the
   exception is rethrown.

=========================================================
Example
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
#include <mutex>

using namespace std;

mutex m1, m2;

int main()
{
    int result = std::try_lock(m1, m2);

    if (result == -1)
    {
        cout << "Both mutexes locked successfully\n";

        m1.unlock();
        m2.unlock();
    }
    else
    {
        cout << "Failed to lock mutex index: "
             << result << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

=========================================================
Important Points
=========================================================

✔ Introduced in C++11.
✔ Used to lock multiple mutexes.
✔ Non-blocking.
✔ Returns -1 if all mutexes are locked.
✔ Returns the zero-based index of the mutex that failed.
✔ Automatically unlocks any previously locked mutexes if a
  lock attempt fails.

=========================================================
Interview Questions
=========================================================

Q. What is std::try_lock()?

std::try_lock() is a C++11 function that attempts to lock
multiple mutexes without blocking. It returns -1 on success
or the index of the mutex that could not be locked.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Why do we use std::try_lock()?

To safely attempt locking multiple mutexes while avoiding
holding a subset of locks if one of the lock attempts fails.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q. Difference between std::mutex::try_lock() and std::try_lock()?

std::mutex::try_lock()

• Member function.
• Locks ONE mutex.
• Returns bool.

std::try_lock()

• Free function.
• Locks MULTIPLE mutexes.
• Returns int (-1 on success).

